===Etymology===
From {{etyl|de}} ''[[Eisberg]]'', compound of ''[[Eis]]'' “ice” + ''[[Berg]]'' “mountain”. First used to describe a glacier as seen at a distance from a ship then used as a term to describe the floating chunks of ice broken off from such glaciers. Compare {{etyl|nl}} ''[[ijsberg]]'', {{etyl|da}} ''[[isbjerg]]'', {{etyl|sv}}/{{etyl|no}} ''[[isberg]]'', Welsh ''[[eisberg]]''.

===Pronunciation===
* {{rhymes|ɜː(r)ɡ}}
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈaɪsbɜːɡ/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A huge mass of ocean-floating [[ice]] which has broken off a [[glacier]] or [[ice shelf]]
#: ''The Titanic hit an '''iceberg''' and sank''.

